I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation to be able to connect with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during the golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We dove directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't that easy to determine.
We had no reason to question the pedestal upon which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundations of our lives.
That's why we're so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the series every Thursday.
It looked like nothing we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in designated closed areas.
Inconsciously, we're dying to reconnect with the universal community that surrounded all this.
That's why we're so many to watch obsessively series like The Office or movies like Presenter Star, with plenty of short references, like memes.
We repeated these refs, knowing that most people already knew them.
Now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't be sure if everyone has seen it.
There are too many things to watch and no way to rationalize them all... will we escape the hypersaturation?
We're caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
We're forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art we connect with can be very flawed.
We're entering parasocial relationships by being more cautious.
We understand that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without stepping on others along the way.
Lack of collective awareness about media has led us to develop a class consciousness that helps us remain critical.
Some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We're in a tumultuous period and I'm eager to see where it will take us.
